        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>While the CO 2-1 line was found to have a line width of 40 km/s from single dish observations, with ALMA we will map the velocity distribution across the full extent of the circumstellar envelope. Therefore, we need to fully resolve the different components of the line profile and request a spectral resolution of ~0.7 km/s. If necessary we will bin the data into 1.5 km/s bins to achieve the requested S/N.
In addition to CO we will also search for other transitions detected in AGB or post-AGB stars: SO, SiO, H2CO, H2S and OCS. These are covered by the three low-resolution FDM spectral windows labelled "continuum". Note that we need the FDM (resolution ~1.5-2.5 km/s) rather than the TDM setup in order to be able to resolve the lines present, and to get a clean measurement of the continuum flux. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We want to fully resolve the structure of the CO 2-1 emission around GX Mon. The Largest Angular Scale is determined by the 5" radius of the arc detected by HST (see Fig. 2). Regardless of whether this turns out to be part of a detached shell like in R Scl or corresponds to an arc as observed in Mira, it gives an indication of the outer boundaries of the gaseous ejecta from the star. Therefore, the requested LAS of 10" will allow us to fully recover the largest-scale emission expected around GX Mon. 
The requested angular resolution of 0.15" was derived from our desire to fully resolve any detached shell or spiral structure in the CO emission. Assuming a distance of ~720 pc for GX Mon (Karovicova et al. 2013), an angular resolution of 0.15" allows us to resolve scales of ~100 AU. Scaling for relative distance, the angular resolution requested is similar to that achieved for the iconic CO observations of R Scl (Maercker et al. 2012), which mapped the spiral structure and detached shell morphology in that star.
Our requested combination of LAS and angular resolution requires a compact plus a more extended 12-m configuration, but no ACA. While the outermost parts of the emission expected will lie just outside the inner 1/3 of the primary beam where maximum sensitivity is reached, we will still reach a S/N &gt; 5 in these regions.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our sensitivity requirement is driven by the CO 2-1 emission that we want to map around the AGB star GX Mon. From Ramstedt et al. (2008) JCMT observations the CO 2-1 line in GX Mon has a peak main beam brightness temperature of ~1.9 K and a total line width of ~40 km/s over the 21" JCMT beam (see Fig. 3). Using the main beam efficiency of 0.66 suggested by these authors and converting to flux assuming a JCMT aperture efficiency of 0.48 yields a peak line flux of 41 Jy. From the HST image of GX Mon (see Fig. 2) we believe the gas around GX Mon to be contained within an area of 10" x 10". Assuming the worst-case scenario where the CO 2-1 flux is uniformly distributed over this area, we would then expect a peak line flux of 9 mJy per ALMA 0.15" x 0.15" synthesised beam. We request a sensitivity of 1.5 mJy per synthesised beam to achieve a minimum S/N=6. The bandwidth for sensitivity was set to 1.5 km/s so as to be sufficient to fully resolve the complex velocity gradient expected across the map.
Since the CO around GX Mon has never been spatially resolved, we can only guess at the morphology of the emission. However, using the emission detected around other AGB stars observed with ALMA such as Mira (Ramstedt et al. 2014) or R Scl (Maercker et al. 2012) as a guideline, we can expect the gas to be organised into shells, arcs and/or spiral structure, implying that the peak line flux per synthesised beam may be several times higher than estimated from our worse-case assumption. This would allow us to trace the emission at higher S/N and better velocity resolution.  
   </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
